ic and self-contained, it is now acknowledged that Europe from the Middle Ages onwards saw increasing flows of people and goods. Movement also connected the continent more closely to other parts of the world. The present work challenges dominant notions of the ‘fixed,’ immobile nature of pre-modern cultures through study of the inter-connected material, social, and cultural dimensions of mobility. The case studies presented here chart the technologies and practices that both facilitated and impeded movement in diverse spheres of social activity such as communication, transport, politics, religion, medicine, and architecture. The chapters underscore the importance of the movement of people and objects through space and across distance to the dynamic economic, political, and cultural life of the early modern period.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aCivilization, ModernxHistory. 0aHuman geographyzEuropexHistory. 0aSocial mobilityzEuropexHistory. 4aEarly Modern Studies. 4aHistory, Art History, and Archaeology. 4aInterdisciplinary Studies. 4aInternational Relations. 4aSociology and Social History. 7aARCHITECTURE / History / Renaissance.2bisacsh  amobility, travel, networks, material culture, early modern Europe, global history.1 aAslanian, Sebouh David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBilić, Darka, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFosi, Irene, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGallagher, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMolino, Paola, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNelles, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNelles, Paul, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 a